03:14.067 --> 03:15.652
<i>I have decided to keep a journal.</i>

03:16.361 --> 03:19.739
<i>Not in a word program or digital file
but in longhand,</i>

03:20.699 --> 03:23.910
<i>writing every word out
so that every inflection of penmanship,</i>

03:24.244 --> 03:27.914
<i>every word chosen, scratched out,
revised, is recorded.</i>

03:29.332 --> 03:31.542
<i>To set down all my thoughts
and the simple events</i>

03:31.625 --> 03:34.086
<i>of my day factually
and without hiding anything.</i>

03:36.255 --> 03:39.049
<i>When writing about oneself,
one should show no mercy.</i>

03:40.801 --> 03:44.179
<i>I will keep this diary
for one year, 12 months</i>

03:45.013 --> 03:47.641
<i>and at the end of that time,
it will be destroyed.</i>

03:48.183 --> 03:51.854
<i>Shredded, then burnt.
The experiment will be over.</i>

04:10.496 --> 04:11.581
Please rise.

04:16.961 --> 04:20.089
What is thy only comfort in life and death?

04:20.839 --> 04:22.258
That I, with body and soul

04:22.341 --> 04:25.595
both in life and death, am not my own

04:25.803 --> 04:29.849
but belong unto
my faithful Savior, Jesus Christ.

04:29.932 --> 04:31.726
Who with his precious blood...

04:31.809 --> 04:34.728
<i>These thoughts and recollections are
not so different from those I confide</i>

04:34.811 --> 04:35.812
<i>to God every morning.</i>

04:38.315 --> 04:39.232
<i>When it is possible.</i>

04:40.108 --> 04:41.151
<i>When he is listening.</i>

04:46.490 --> 04:48.825
Bread of life. The cup of salvation.

04:55.207 --> 04:57.584
The bread of life. The cup of salvation.

05:00.962 --> 05:02.964
The bread of life. The cup of salvation.

05:03.048 --> 05:04.966
<i>This journal is a form of speaking...</i>

05:06.383 --> 05:09.303
<i>of communication from one to the other.</i>

05:10.179 --> 05:12.306
<i>A communication which can be achieved simply</i>

05:13.140 --> 05:15.726
<i>and in repose without
prostration or abnegation.</i>

05:18.604 --> 05:19.730
<i>It is a form of prayer.</i>

05:21.106 --> 05:23.692
Bread of life. The cup of salvation.

05:33.828 --> 05:36.330
There is a leak in the men's restroom.

05:36.413 --> 05:37.330
No, I fixed it.

05:37.413 --> 05:41.793
No. I was just there. It's still leaking.
Same place. Under the hot faucet.

05:41.876 --> 05:44.462
- What about the women's room?
- The women's is fine.

05:44.796 --> 05:46.506
Do you want me to call
the plumber from Abundant Life?

05:46.589 --> 05:47.966
No, let me have another crack at it.

05:48.049 --> 05:50.301
I hate always bugging them
for extra little costs.

05:50.385 --> 05:52.095
They don't mind.
That's what they're there for.

05:52.178 --> 05:54.806
- And you're totally within your budget.
- Still, I don't want to.

05:56.391 --> 05:57.433
Have you posted the sermon?

05:57.892 --> 05:59.644
Yes. I did it this morning.

06:01.437 --> 06:02.355
- Oh...
- Reverend?

06:02.438 --> 06:04.482
Yes, Mary, right?

06:04.566 --> 06:06.860
- Mary Mensana.
- Yeah, nice to see you again.

06:07.193 --> 06:09.111
I wanted to talk, if that's okay.

06:09.194 --> 06:10.571
Yeah, yeah, yeah. Come on in, Mary.

06:10.654 --> 06:13.365
- I'll be right back.
- Mary, how can I help you?

06:13.448 --> 06:14.533
I was wondering if you would talk

06:14.616 --> 06:16.368
- to my husband, Michael.
- Oh, sure. I...

06:16.451 --> 06:18.287
Actually, not now.
He has to... he has to go to work.

06:18.370 --> 06:19.705
He has to fill in at Home Depot.

06:22.541 --> 06:23.458
Mary?

06:25.085 --> 06:27.129
- What is it?
- I'm worried about him.

06:27.838 --> 06:29.673
He's involved in the Green Planet movement.

06:29.756 --> 06:31.425
- It's an activist group.
- Mm-hmm.

06:31.508 --> 06:33.260
And he was in jail in Canada.

06:33.886 --> 06:35.387
And he just got out two weeks ago.

06:35.762 --> 06:38.640
He just sits around at home.
He doesn't... he doesn't go out.

06:38.724 --> 06:42.476
I got him to fill out a temp form
for Home... for Home Depot.

06:42.560 --> 06:44.145
- Okay.
- So that's good.

06:44.228 --> 06:45.938
Are you sure you don't want
to go to Abundant Life?

06:46.022 --> 06:47.857
They have a whole team
of counselors over there,

06:47.940 --> 06:49.859
- who are trained and...
- I know, but he doesn't want to.

06:49.942 --> 06:51.777
He thinks it's more
of a company than a church.

06:52.153 --> 06:54.071
And so, he said he would talk to you.

06:56.282 --> 06:57.199
Uh, all right.

06:58.284 --> 06:59.201
Tomorrow?

07:00.077 --> 07:01.621
- After lunch?
- Great. Great.

07:01.704 --> 07:03.789
I'll just need the... I just need an address.

07:04.415 --> 07:05.666
And can you tell me a little more?

07:06.876 --> 07:09.879
Oh, he applied for compassionate release
when he found out.

07:09.962 --> 07:11.964
He was at Fort Providence.
They let him out early.

07:12.048 --> 07:14.966
- Wait, now, found out what?
- That I was pregnant.

07:15.050 --> 07:18.178
Oh. Hmm, congratulations.

07:18.887 --> 07:19.804
Thanks.

07:21.398 --> 07:24.734
He thinks it's wrong to bring
a child into this world.

07:28.196 --> 07:30.490
He wants to kill our baby.

07:35.787 --> 07:38.373
<i>I assisted Sunday the youth group
at Abundant Life.</i>

07:38.832 --> 07:41.501
<i>The young people were
so excited, so full of life.</i>

07:41.918 --> 07:43.878
<i>They were open. They welcomed communion.</i>

07:48.298 --> 07:50.592
<i>Maybe I shouldn't care about
whether people like me.</i>

07:52.651 --> 07:54.653
<i>Did Jesus worry about being liked?</i>

07:58.824 --> 08:01.201
<i>I look at the last lines
I wrote with disdain.</i>

08:05.038 --> 08:05.956
<i>Twelve months.</i>

08:07.249 --> 08:09.209
<i>Can I keep up an exercise that long?</i>

08:23.723 --> 08:26.517
<i>When I read these words,
I see not truth, but pride.</i>

08:32.732 --> 08:34.442
<i>I wish I had not used the word pride.</i>

08:35.735 --> 08:37.193
<i>But I cannot cross it out.</i>

08:42.658 --> 08:44.118
<i>If only I could pray.</i>

09:41.358 --> 09:42.275
Hi, Reverend.

09:42.359 --> 09:45.820
- Hi. Is Michael home?
- Yeah. Come on in.

09:45.904 --> 09:46.988
Okay. Yeah.

09:51.117 --> 09:53.243
- Hey. Good to see you.
- Nice to see you.

09:53.786 --> 09:55.496
Um, would you like some coffee?

09:56.372 --> 09:59.375
- Yes, but, um...
- We're... I think we have some tea.

09:59.458 --> 10:00.584
Yes. That would be better.

10:00.668 --> 10:01.585
- Okay.
- Thanks.

10:04.588 --> 10:06.090
Let me take your coat?

10:06.924 --> 10:08.300
No, it's okay. I got it.

10:09.426 --> 10:10.344
Come on in.

10:15.766 --> 10:18.811
- Yeah, I don't know why Mary...
- There's no need to apologize.

10:19.144 --> 10:21.855
No, she told me
that you've been up in Canada.

10:22.898 --> 10:25.942
Yeah. Fort Providence.

10:26.943 --> 10:30.071
It's in the Mackenzie Delta.
It's way in the north.

10:30.154 --> 10:31.823
Yeah, beautiful country, I imagine.

10:31.906 --> 10:33.116
Yeah, it is.

10:37.328 --> 10:38.830
Mary said things have been getting you down?

10:41.624 --> 10:45.545
Uh, yeah, things.
Yeah, you could say that. Yeah.

10:46.879 --> 10:48.339
Oh! Thank you very much.

10:49.007 --> 10:50.049
- It's hot.
- Perfect.

10:51.175 --> 10:52.093
Thank you.

11:01.810 --> 11:03.729
- So Mary is pregnant.
- Hmm.

11:04.479 --> 11:08.358
- Yeah. How far along is she?
- Twenty weeks.

11:08.692 --> 11:10.110
- Congratulations.
- Thanks.

11:18.702 --> 11:21.329
Hey, how old are you, Reverend?

11:23.832 --> 11:24.750
I'm 46.

11:28.586 --> 11:29.879
Uh, 33.

11:31.797 --> 11:34.925
That's how old our child will be in 2050.

11:35.009 --> 11:36.594
Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm. Yeah.

11:36.677 --> 11:39.388
You know, that's
two years older than I am right now.

11:39.472 --> 11:40.514
Mm-hmm.

11:41.974 --> 11:44.351
- You'll be 81.
- Yeah!

11:45.269 --> 11:49.315
Hey, you know what the world
will be like in 2050?

11:49.398 --> 11:52.193
- Hmm. Hard to imagine.
- Yeah, you think?

11:53.778 --> 11:59.491
I mean, Reverend,
the world is changing so fast.

12:00.617 --> 12:01.701
And right in front of us.

12:01.785 --> 12:06.331
I mean, one-third of the natural world
has been destroyed in your lifetime.

12:07.791 --> 12:11.377
You know, the earth's temperature
will be three degrees centigrade higher.

12:12.378 --> 12:13.671
Four is the threshold.

12:15.048 --> 12:19.010
You know, "Severe, widespread,
and irreversible impacts."

12:19.094 --> 12:23.014
And when scientists say
stuff like that, you know?

12:23.098 --> 12:25.517
And National Center
for Atmospheric Research...

12:27.852 --> 12:31.063
Lawrence Livermore,
Potsdam Institute. Reverend...

12:31.146 --> 12:32.856
<i>He went on like that for some time.</i>

12:33.649 --> 12:36.902
<i>By 2050, sea levels two feet
higher on the East Coast.</i>

12:37.361 --> 12:40.030
<i>Low lying areas underwater across the world.</i>

12:40.280 --> 12:42.783
<i>Bangladesh, 20% loss of landmass.</i>

12:42.866 --> 12:46.036
<i>Central Africa, 50% reduction
in crops due to drought.</i>

12:46.411 --> 12:48.038
<i>The Western reservoirs dried up.</i>

12:48.122 --> 12:51.208
<i>Climate change. Refugees.
Epidemics. Extreme weather.</i>

12:51.667 --> 12:52.709
You know, the...

12:54.419 --> 12:56.338
the bad times, they will begin,

12:56.421 --> 12:58.549
and from that point,
everything moves very quickly.

13:00.467 --> 13:05.012
You know, this social structure
can't bear the stress of multiple crises.

13:06.430 --> 13:09.976
Opportunistic diseases, anarchy,
martial law, the tipping point.

13:10.059 --> 13:12.061
And this isn't in some, like, distant future.

13:12.145 --> 13:13.437
You will live to see this.

13:14.355 --> 13:18.526
You know, my children
will experience this un-livability.

13:18.609 --> 13:19.735
This, uh...

13:20.528 --> 13:22.321
Yeah, I'm sorry. I just... you know, I...

13:23.322 --> 13:25.241
I thought things could change, you know?

13:25.324 --> 13:27.118
I thought... I thought people would listen.

13:27.869 --> 13:29.245
Do you have thoughts of harming yourself?

13:31.914 --> 13:32.832
No.

13:34.082 --> 13:36.126
Why? Did Mary say something like that?

13:36.209 --> 13:37.127
No, no.

13:37.460 --> 13:39.296
No, I'm not worried for myself.

13:39.880 --> 13:43.758
I just... this world is gonna be what it is.

13:45.051 --> 13:46.970
- But can I ask you a question, Reverend?
- Mm-hmm.

13:49.139 --> 13:51.975
How do you sanction
bringing in a little girl...

13:52.684 --> 13:56.188
Uh, for argument's sake,
let's just say that, uh...

13:56.646 --> 13:59.733
Mary and I's child, it's a little girl.

14:05.030 --> 14:07.364
You know, a child that's so full of hope...

14:09.241 --> 14:13.829
and naive beliefs into a world
where that little girl, uh...

14:15.789 --> 14:19.668
she grows up to be a young woman
and she looks you in the eyes

14:19.752 --> 14:22.630
and she says that you knew
this all along, didn't you?

14:27.468 --> 14:28.385
You see, that...

14:30.638 --> 14:33.140
I mean, what are you supposed to say then?

14:36.602 --> 14:38.478
There's something growing inside Mary.

14:39.145 --> 14:43.691
Something as alive as a tree, surely.

14:44.275 --> 14:46.152
As an endangered species.

14:47.278 --> 14:51.491
Something full of the beauty
and mystery of nature.

14:54.077 --> 14:56.996
You said sanction, hmm?

14:58.539 --> 15:00.083
You think Mary should have an abortion?

15:00.792 --> 15:02.293
This birth, is that your right?

15:02.377 --> 15:03.419
Is that your decision?

15:03.878 --> 15:05.463
Have you asked Mary what she thinks?

15:11.760 --> 15:15.639
Look, this isn't... it's not about your baby.

15:16.640 --> 15:17.641
It's not about Mary.

15:19.893 --> 15:21.103
It's about you...

15:22.437 --> 15:24.648
and your despair. Your lack of hope.

15:26.275 --> 15:28.652
Look, people have throughout history

15:28.735 --> 15:32.739
have woken up in the dead of the night
confronted by blackness.

15:33.282 --> 15:35.409
The sense that our lives are without meaning.

15:37.202 --> 15:38.495
<i>The Sickness Unto Death.</i>

15:38.578 --> 15:40.247
Yeah, but this is something different.

15:40.330 --> 15:42.164
Yeah, no, man's great achievements

15:42.248 --> 15:45.918
have brought him to the place
where life as we know it

15:46.002 --> 15:47.753
may cease in the foreseeable future.

15:47.837 --> 15:48.879
Yes, that's new.

15:50.131 --> 15:51.090
But the blackness?

15:53.759 --> 15:54.677
That's not.

15:55.011 --> 15:57.013
We're scientific people.
We want to solve things.

15:57.096 --> 15:58.764
We want rational answers.

15:59.181 --> 16:03.394
Right? And if humankind can't overcome

16:03.477 --> 16:06.939
its immediate interests enough to ensure
its own survival, then you're right.

16:07.023 --> 16:09.442
The only rational response is despair.

16:11.068 --> 16:15.113
But do you think that
there's any existence apart from this?

16:15.947 --> 16:17.407
This here, right now?

16:17.490 --> 16:18.825
- Yes.
- Yeah, right, before us.

16:18.908 --> 16:19.826
- After us.
- Yeah.

16:19.909 --> 16:21.911
- Yeah,
- Wait, so you're talking about

16:21.995 --> 16:23.288
the next lifetime? Huh?

16:23.788 --> 16:24.831
You really... you just, uh...

16:24.914 --> 16:28.043
<i>I felt like I was Jacob wrestling
all night long with the angel.</i>

16:28.835 --> 16:30.045
<i>Fighting in the grasp.</i>

16:31.296 --> 16:34.883
<i>Every sentence, every question,
every response, a mortal struggle.</i>

16:35.967 --> 16:37.260
<i>It was exhilarating.</i>

16:38.011 --> 16:39.804
You believe in martyrdom, Reverend?

16:39.888 --> 16:41.222
I'm not sure I know what you mean.

16:41.306 --> 16:42.724
You know, the Saints of God?

16:43.141 --> 16:46.018
The early Christians
who wouldn't renounce their faith?

16:46.518 --> 16:49.313
The missionaries who were attacked
in the fields of the Lord.

16:49.396 --> 16:51.273
Do you believe that they died for a purpose?

16:51.357 --> 16:53.067
- I do.
- Well, every week,

16:53.150 --> 16:56.653
activists are killed
trying to protect the environment.

16:58.530 --> 17:01.700
A hundred and seventeen were
killed last year for their beliefs.

17:04.036 --> 17:05.162
I mean, right there.

17:05.244 --> 17:08.207
This is JosÃ© ClÃ¡udio Ribeiro da Silva.

17:09.290 --> 17:11.794
Huh? And that's his wife, Maria.

17:14.213 --> 17:19.800
Uh... they were... they were gunned down
in 2011 in the Amazon.

17:21.344 --> 17:24.880
You know, they were protesting
free cutting of the rain forest.

17:25.765 --> 17:29.852
Hey, this is Dorothy Stang, 2005.

17:29.936 --> 17:32.814
She was a nun from Ohio.

17:35.400 --> 17:37.610
And what was the purpose of their death?

17:45.201 --> 17:48.870
You know, in 2010, the IPCC predicted

17:48.954 --> 17:52.165
that if drastic action wasn't taken by 2015,

17:53.667 --> 17:55.836
environmental collapse would be irreversible.

17:57.045 --> 17:58.130
And nothing was done.

18:01.633 --> 18:03.385
And now it's 2017.

18:04.636 --> 18:07.389
You said you respected me.
What I've been through.

18:09.766 --> 18:14.604
- Yes.
- So you know my story, hmm?

18:15.188 --> 18:16.982
- Yeah, you were a chaplain.
- Uh-huh.

18:17.607 --> 18:21.444
My father taught at VMI.
I encouraged my son to enlist.

18:21.527 --> 18:22.945
It was the family tradition.

18:23.988 --> 18:28.325
Like his father, my father before me, hmm.

18:28.409 --> 18:29.910
A patriotic tradition.

18:33.664 --> 18:36.834
My wife... was very opposed.

18:37.877 --> 18:39.295
My son enlisted anyway.

18:39.795 --> 18:42.840
And six months later, he was dead in Iraq.

18:43.257 --> 18:49.555
Right? I talked my son into a war
that had no moral justification.

18:52.307 --> 18:53.975
My wife could no longer live with me.

18:55.018 --> 18:56.102
I left the military.

18:57.896 --> 18:58.813
I was lost.

19:01.691 --> 19:04.027
And Reverend Jeffers from Abundant Life,

19:04.110 --> 19:08.031
he gave me this position
at First Reformed and here I am.

19:08.114 --> 19:10.533
And Michael, I can promise you...

19:11.951 --> 19:16.956
that whatever despair you feel
about bringing a child into this world

19:17.540 --> 19:21.836
cannot equal the despair
of taking a child from it.

19:34.223 --> 19:36.058
Hey, what was his name?

19:37.267 --> 19:38.185
Your son?

19:40.729 --> 19:41.647
Joseph.

19:43.690 --> 19:44.650
The boy thrown down the well.

19:44.733 --> 19:46.652
- Yeah, I remember.
- Mm-hmm.

19:46.735 --> 19:49.363
- The dreamer.
- The dreamer, yeah. Yeah.

19:54.326 --> 19:55.993
And you were able to just go on?

19:57.161 --> 20:00.998
Courage... is the solution to despair.

20:01.332 --> 20:05.044
Reason... provides no answers.

20:07.171 --> 20:09.090
I can't know what the future will bring.

20:09.173 --> 20:11.926
We have to choose despite uncertainty.

20:13.177 --> 20:19.892
Wisdom is holding two contradictory truths
in our mind, simultaneously.

20:21.060 --> 20:22.895
Hope and despair.

20:22.979 --> 20:25.189
A life without despair
is a life without hope.

20:25.273 --> 20:28.942
Holding these two ideas
in our head is life itself.

20:44.416 --> 20:45.750
Are you a drinking man, Reverend?

20:47.002 --> 20:49.963
- It doesn't help.
- No, I suppose not.

20:57.887 --> 20:59.055
Can God forgive us?

21:04.018 --> 21:05.769
For what we've done to this world?

21:08.230 --> 21:09.231
I don't know.

21:11.942 --> 21:13.402
Who can know the mind of God?

21:15.904 --> 21:16.864
But we can choose...

21:19.700 --> 21:20.743
a righteous life.

21:22.077 --> 21:23.078
Belief.

21:24.163 --> 21:25.331
Forgiveness.

21:27.499 --> 21:29.877
Grace covers us all.

21:32.754 --> 21:33.838
I believe that.

21:42.805 --> 21:44.515
Let's meet again.

21:44.974 --> 21:45.892
Want to?

21:46.559 --> 21:48.436
Tomorrow after lunch, same time.

21:49.437 --> 21:51.356
Okay, yeah. It's a... it's a plan.

21:55.318 --> 21:58.446
<i>I went over everything that was said,
what should have been said,</i>

21:58.529 --> 22:00.323
<i>what could have been said differently,</i>

22:00.406 --> 22:01.783
<i>what could have been said better.</i>

22:03.784 --> 22:07.329
<i>"I know that nothing can change
and I know there is no hope."</i>

22:08.914 --> 22:10.207
<i>Thomas Merton wrote this.</i>

22:13.460 --> 22:16.338
<i>"Despair is a development of pride so great</i>

22:16.421 --> 22:18.465
<i>that it chooses one's certitude</i>

22:18.548 --> 22:22.010
<i>rather than admit God
is more creative than we are."</i>

22:23.553 --> 22:25.472
<i>Perhaps it's better I didn't say that to him.</i>

23:04.176 --> 23:05.970
<i>Who am I to talk about pride?</i>

23:26.156 --> 23:30.577
Well, to begin, the church
was constructed in 1767

23:30.660 --> 23:32.537
in a style we now call Dutch colonial.

23:33.079 --> 23:36.750
It was made by settlers... follow me...
using local timber.

23:37.250 --> 23:39.793
First Reformed took seven years to build.

23:40.627 --> 23:41.545
The Vei Plancks.

23:42.129 --> 23:44.923
Effie here, her tombstone dates back to 1787.

23:45.424 --> 23:49.595
The church was partially rebuilt
in 1837 following a fire.

23:50.304 --> 23:52.848
This section remains preserved.

23:53.474 --> 23:57.186
If you look closely behind
the Continental Army flag,

23:57.269 --> 23:59.438
you'll find two bullet holes

23:59.521 --> 24:03.025
from shots fired during
the Skirmish of Snowbridge.

24:04.193 --> 24:07.821
In two months we're celebrating
our 250th anniversary.

24:08.739 --> 24:11.365
Here is an example of some
of the church's chinaware

24:11.449 --> 24:12.867
brought over from the Netherlands.

24:13.159 --> 24:15.453
And the first chalice. It's beautiful.

24:15.828 --> 24:19.248
And here, this is the original key
from the front door before the fire.

24:19.332 --> 24:20.666
Isn't that neat? Yeah.

24:20.750 --> 24:24.295
And in that cabinet we have
souvenirs that are for sale.

24:24.378 --> 24:29.300
We have mugs, caps, postcards,
key chains, pens, t-shirts.

24:29.383 --> 24:30.343
What size are these?

24:30.426 --> 24:31.844
Unfortunately, they are all small.

24:31.928 --> 24:34.597
